site_name: Phase 6 Of The South Acton Estate
description: Reserved matters application for Phase 6 of the Acton Gardens masterplan detailing Landscaping, Appearance, Scale, Access and Layout in relation to the construction of two buildings varying between six and ten storeys high containing 308 residential units; provision of Class A1, A3, B1 and D1 uses at ground floor including the provision of a Community Centre, Youth Centre, Nursery/Early Start, Medical Centre, Cafe, offices and retail units, and provision of public open space; associated private and semi-private amenity space, refuse/recycling and bicycle storage, energy plant rooms, on and off-street parking spaces, works to public highway and public realm improvements, following the demolition of Charles Hocking House, Hardy Court and Oak Tree community centre; application made part pursuant to Conditions 2 (Reserved Matters), 4 (Reserved Matters Details), 5 (Details of Public Realm Landscaping), 6 (Energy Strategy), 11 (Noise Mitigation Measures), 16 (Flood Risk Assessment), 18 (Tree Protection), 19 (Refuse and Recycling Enclosures), 20 (Archaeological Investigation), 22 (Rainwater and / or Greywater Recycling Systems), 25 (Boundary Treatments), 26 (CCTV, Security Lighting, Post Boxes, Entry Systems) of outline planning permission LBE ref: P/2012/0708, dated 13/08/2013 (amended by minor material amendment application PP/2014/2142 dated 21/07/2014 and P/2014/6303 dated 31/03/2015) for the multi-Phased regeneration of the South Acton Estate.
decision_conditions: The development hereby approved shall be carried out in accordance with the following approved plans and documents:

Drawings: (3245A-P-) 100 P6, 101 P10, 102 P11, 103 P15, 104 P5, 105 P6, 106 P6, 107 P6, 108 P6, 109 P5, 110 P5, 111 P4, 200 P4, 201 P5, 202 P5, 203 P6, 204 P6, 205 P3; (3245-L-) 900, 901, 902, 903, 904, 905, 906, 910, 911, 912. Technical Documents: Archaeology - Written Scheme of Investigation dated 14/01/2016 prepared by Pre-Construct Archaeology Ltd; BREEAM Technical Justification Version 2 dated 04/03/2016 prepared by Hodkinson Consultancy; Daylight and Sunlight Report (Discharging planning condition 4) Version 4 dated 01/03/2016 prepared by Hodkinson Consultancy; Design and Access Statement (Discharging planning conditions 4, 5, 19, 21, 25) ref: 3245A Rev P3 dated 08/03/2016 prepared by Levitt Bernstein; Energy Statement (including overheating assessment) (Discharging planning condition 6) Version 4 dated 26/02/2016 prepared by Hodkinson Consultancy; Foul and Surface Water Drainage Scheme (Discharging planning condition 16) ref: A3197/MOM/AJC Rev F1 dated 12/02/2016 prepared by CTP Consulting Engineers; Planning Statement (Discharging planning condition 4) ref: 180603H dated March 2016 prepared by Terence O'Rourke; Planning Supporting statement Appendix 1 Affordable Housing Statement dated March 2016 prepared by Acton Gardens LLP; Planning Supporting Statement Appendix 2 Estate Management Plan dated March 2016 prepared by Acton Gardens LLP; Residential Travel Plan ref: ITB11142-002C R dated 06/03/2016 prepared by i-Transport LLP; Statement of community Involvement (Discharging planning condition 4) dated March 2016 prepared by Levitt Bernstein and Acton Gardens LLP; Tree Protection Details and Arboricultural Statement ref: 1015-1822 Final dated February 2016 prepared by Ruskins Group Consultancy; Sustainability Statement (including BREEAM and Code for Sustainable Homes Pre-Assessments) (Discharging planning conditions 4, 21 and 22) Version 3 Final prepared by Hodkinson Consultancy; Transport Statement ref: ITB11142-001C dated 06/03/2016 prepared by i-Transport LLP; Water Statement ref: J2163 dated 07/03/2016 prepared by Mendick Waring Ltd; Response to LB Ealing energy and sustainability comments dated May 2016 preapred by Hodkinson Consultancy.
Reason: For the avoidance of doubt and in the interests of proper planning.

| The development hereby approved shall be constructed to achieve a water use target of 105 litres per person per day for the 308 residential dwellings in accordance with the approved Water Statement ref: J2163 dated 07/03/2016 prepared by Mendick Waring Ltd.
Reason: To ensure that the development achieves the sustainable use of water in accordance with policy 5.15 of the London Plan (2016).

| Prior to the commencement of superstructure works on each of the approved apartment buildings (Block 6.1 and Block 6.2), the details of the dynamic thermal modelling for that apartment building (including the non-residential floorspace), using the guidance provided in CIBSE TM49 & TM52 and demonstrating how the development performs against the overheating criteria shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The details of any additional measures to be incorporated into the development to minimise the risk of overheating (without active cooling) shall also be submitted if the dynamic thermal modelling demonstrates that overheating would occur. The development shall thereafter be provided in accordance with the approved details.
Reason: To ensure that the risk of overheating has been sufficiently addressed in accordance with policy 5.9 of the London Plan (2016).

| The development hereby approved shall be constructed to achieve compliance with the commitments set out within the approved Design & Access Statement and as indicated on the approved plans in relation to 90% of the dwellings meeting Part M4(2) and the remaining 10% of dwellings meeting Part M4(3) of the Building Regulations 2015.

Reason: To ensure that the new dwellings are designed and constructed to be adaptable, accessible and flexible in accordance with policies 3.5, 3.8 and 3.9 of the London Plan (2016) and policy 1.1(h) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012).

| Prior to the first occupation of any part of the development hereby approved, a Delivery and Servicing Plan shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The development shall thereafter operate in accordance with the approved Delivery and Servicing Plan.

Reason: To ensure that the resulting servicing arrangements are satisfactory in terms of their impact on highway safety and the free-flow of traffic in accordance with policies 6.7 and 6.13 of the London Plan (2016).
